Apollon is an educational modeling tool used by students and instructors to create, share, and assess software diagrams. It is available as a reusable editor, a standalone web application, a mobile application, and part of the Artemis learning platform. This broad use creates a need for consistent and accessible modeling workflows across different devices and teaching scenarios.

Before this thesis, several interactions required unnecessary manual effort, collaborators had limited awareness of each other's activity, and important workflows differed between applications. The coexistence of a legacy editor and a reengineered Apollon version also complicated maintenance and integration. These limitations affected diagram creation, collaborative exercises, mobile use, assessment, and export.

This thesis improves the usability and integration of the Apollon ecosystem through an iterative development process. The work simplifies diagram editing, introduces collaboration awareness, improves diagram management and mobile export, and makes visual exports more reliable. It also integrates the maintained Apollon version into Artemis, preserves quiz and assessment workflows, supports existing model versions in Athena, and updates the VS Code extension. The resulting work provides a more consistent foundation for modeling across individual study, teamwork, teaching, and assessment contexts.
